If $A = (3,4)$ and $C = (7,10)$ are opposite vertices of a rectangle $ABCD,$ then vertices $A, B, C,$ and $D$ must lie on the circle
\[x^2 + y^2 - px - qy + s = 0.\]Compute the ordered triple of real numbers $(p,q,s).$
natural solution: Since $\angle ABC = \angle ADC = 90^\circ,$ $\overline{AC}$ must be a diameter of this circle. [asy] unitsize (0.8 cm); pair A, B, C, D, O; A = (3,4); C = (7,10); O = (A + C)/2; B = O + abs(O - A)*dir(170);

D = O + abs(O - A)*dir(350); draw(Circle(O,abs(O - A))); draw(A--C); draw(B--D); draw(A--B--C--D--cycle); label("$A$", A, SW); label("$B$", B, W); label("$C$", C, NE); label("$D$", D, E); dot(O); [/asy]

The center of the circle is then $(5,7)$ (the mid-point of $A$ and $C$), and its radius is $\sqrt{(5 - 3)^2 + (7 - 4)^2} = \sqrt{13},$ so its equation is \[(x - 5)^2 + (y - 7)^2 = 13.\]This simplifies to $x^2 + y^2 - 10x - 14y + 61 = 0,$ so $(p,q,s) = \boxed{(10,14,61)}.$

theorem
fixes A :: "real*real" and C :: "real*real"
assumes h0 : "A = (3,4)"
and h1 : "C = (7,10)"
and h2 : "\<forall> B D. B \<noteq> D \<longrightarrow> (\<exists>p q s. \<forall>x y. (x,y) = B \<or> (x,y) = D \<longrightarrow> x powr 2 + y powr 2 - p*x - q*y + s = 0)"
shows  "(p,q,s) = (10,14,61)"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
a_9.informal problem: Given the points A (3, 4) and C (7, 10), find the coefficients p, q, and s of the general form of a circle equation $x^2 + y^2 - px - qy + s = 0$ that passes through points B and D. B and D are distinct points, and each point can be either A or C. The final answer is (p, q, s) = (10, 14, 61).
